Yes, it is absolutely possible to shift the hamburger icon to the left when the sidebar is open using CSS, as you suggested. The idea is to add a class like `.shifted` to the hamburger icon whenever the sidebar is open, and then use CSS to move it accordingly.

Here’s how you can achieve this behavior using the existing checkbox (`#toggle-sidebar`) to control both the sidebar and the hamburger icon's position:

### Updated Code to Shift Hamburger Icon:

1. **HTML Structure**:

```html
<header>
  <div class="logo">My Logo</div>
  <label for="toggle-sidebar" class="hamburger">
    <span></span>
    <span></span>
    <span></span>
  </label>
</header>

<input type="checkbox" id="toggle-sidebar">
<div id="sidebar">
  <div class="close-btn">&times;</div>
  <p>Custom text goes here.</p>
</div>
<div class="overlay"></div>
```

2. **CSS Code**:

```css
/* Basic styles for the header and hamburger */
header {
  position: fixed;
  top: 0;
  left: 0;
  width: 100%;
  background: #333;
  color: #fff;
  padding: 1rem;
  z-index: 1000;
  display: flex;
  justify-content: space-between;
  align-items: center;
}

.hamburger {
  display: none;
  cursor: pointer;
  transition: transform 0.4s ease; /* Added transition for smooth shifting */
}

.hamburger span {
  display: block;
  width: 25px;
  height: 3px;
  margin: 5px;
  background: #fff;
}

/* Media query to display hamburger only on mobile */
@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .hamburger {
    display: block;
  }
}

/* Sidebar Styles */
#sidebar {
  position: fixed;
  top: 0;
  right: -300px;
  width: 300px;
  height: 100%;
  background: #444;
  color: #fff;
  padding: 2rem;
  box-shadow: -2px 0 5px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5);
  transition: right 0.4s ease;
}

#sidebar .close-btn {
  position: absolute;
  top: 10px;
  right: 10px;
  cursor: pointer;
  font-size: 1.5rem;
}

/* Checkbox to toggle sidebar */
#toggle-sidebar {
  display: none;
}

/* Show sidebar when checkbox is checked */
#toggle-sidebar:checked + #sidebar {
  right: 0;
}

/* Overlay Effect */
#toggle-sidebar:checked ~ .overlay {
  display: block;
}

.overlay {
  display: none;
  position: fixed;
  top: 0;
  left: 0;
  width: 100%;
  height: 100%;
  background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5);
  z-index: 900;
}

/* When sidebar is open, shift hamburger icon to the left */
#toggle-sidebar:checked ~ header .hamburger {
  transform: translateX(-300px); /* Shift to the left by 300px */
}
```

### Explanation:

1. **HTML Changes**:
   - No changes needed in the HTML; we continue using the checkbox (`#toggle-sidebar`) to manage the state of the sidebar and hamburger.

2. **CSS Changes**:
   - Added a **transition** to the `.hamburger` class for smooth movement.
   - Used the selector `#toggle-sidebar:checked ~ header .hamburger` to target the hamburger icon when the sidebar is open.
   - The CSS rule `transform: translateX(-300px);` is applied to shift the hamburger icon to the left when the sidebar is open. The value `-300px` matches the sidebar width, ensuring that the hamburger icon is shifted appropriately.

### How It Works:
- When the checkbox (`#toggle-sidebar`) is **checked**, the `#sidebar` slides in from the right.
- At the same time, the hamburger icon (`.hamburger`) is shifted to the left by **300px** using the `transform: translateX(-300px);` rule.
- The `transition` property makes the movement of the hamburger icon smooth.

This solution allows for a nice animation that moves the hamburger icon out of the way when the sidebar is open, providing a clean user experience without overlapping elements.

